[2] Missouri (Lawrence County): commercial turkeys
Date: Thu 24 Mar 2022 07:00 CDT
Source: Lawrence County Record [edited]
http://www.lawrencecountyrecord.com/content/avian-influenza-infects-flock-almost-38000-turkeys-law-co


A flock of 37 770 commercial turkeys that were being raised in Lawrence County were confirmed to be infected with avian influenza (AI). The United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) stated on their website the birds were confirmed to be infected on Wed 9 Mar 2022. The flock has since been "depopulated," a commonly used term for killed.

According to information from the Missouri Department of Agriculture (MDA), AI viruses are influenza type A viruses that naturally occur in bird populations and transmitted from bird to bird "through fecal droppings, saliva, and nasal discharges." Infections in humans are rare.

Besides the case in Lawrence County, 4 other cases of AI have been confirmed in Missouri, according to the USDA website. The first confirmed case was in Stoddard County, where the USDA confirmed on 4 Mar 2022 a flock of 360 000 commercial broiler chickens were infected. That same day, they also confirmed a flock of 51 "backyard mixed species" of non-poultry birds in Bates County were also infected. A flock of 25 015 commercial turkeys in Jasper County were discovered to be infected on 8 Mar 2022, and the latest confirmation was in Ralls County, where 75 non-poultry birds were found to be infected on 15 Mar 2022. All of the infected birds were depopulated.

Christi Miller, communications director for the MDA, said it was unknown how the birds in the confirmed cases were infected. According to information from the MDA website, the virus can be transmitted to birds in the North American flyways when they intermingle with birds from Europe and Asia. "Positive tests in wild waterfowl can occur, and waterfowl can be infected and show no signs of illness," website stated. "There is a risk for spillover from wild birds into domestic poultry and then spill back from poultry to wild birds, resulting in further spread." The MDA stated some of the warning signs a flock has been infected include a decrease in water or feed consumption, respiratory signs such as coughing and sneezing, quietness among the flock, a decrease in egg production and a sudden increase of death in the flock.

Poultry growers are being asked to take precautions to prevent the spread of AI. Among these are restricting visitors from access to their flocks, preventing flocks from having contact from wild birds, and refraining from visiting other poultry growers. Other suggestions include having a set of clothing and footwear only worn when working with their birds, disinfecting footwear before entering barns or coops, and washing hands before and after handling birds.

Poultry growers are also asked to reduce any availability of food, water and nesting areas for wild birds and to fix any holes in roofs, screens and walls of poultry coops to keep wild birds from entering. Likewise, it is recommended that poultry growers clean and disinfect the wheels of any vehicle that has been to another poultry farm, as well as clean and disinfect any equipment that another poultry grower has borrowed and returned.

Any poultry grower who suspects their birds may be infected should immediately contact their local veterinarian or MDA Animal Health Division. Miller stated the names of all poultry growers whose flocks are found to be infected are kept confidential. The MDA also stated chicken and other poultry products are safe to eat if cooked properly, and none of the infected birds are in the food supply. They also stated US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention considers the risk for infection to the general public to be low.

[byline: Steve Chapman]

