[4] Maine (Cumberland County): mixed flocks
Date: Fri 25 Mar 2022
Source: Bangor Daily News [edited]
https://bangordailynews.com/2022/03/25/news/cumberland-is-5th-maine-county-to-report-avian-flu-cases/


More cases of the deadly avian influenza have been reported in Cumberland County. The cases affected a mixed flock of about 150 poultry and were reported on 22 Mar 2022, according to the US Department of Agriculture. The H5N1 avian influenza, a deadly disease that was first identified in Maine in a small flock in Knox County in February [2022], has the state on high alert. Keepers of backyard poultry flocks are being urged to take every precaution to prevent its spread. Cases also have been detected in Washington, Knox, Lincoln and York counties. So far in Maine it has been found in both domestic and wild birds.

Symptoms include swollen heads, blue coloration of combs and wattles, lack of appetite, respiratory distress and diarrhea with a significant drop in egg production. These symptoms are particularly severe in chickens and turkeys.

If there is any question about the health of an individual bird or entire flock, it is crucial to report those cases to state officials.

[byline: Leela Stockley]

--
communicated by:
ProMED rapporteur Mahmoud Orabi

[If possible, keep your flocks inside to protect them from co-mingling with wild birds. And remember you can transport this virus on boots, or hands or even your coveralls. Be sure you are in clean gear before entering your birdhouses, and also blow your nose before entering a poultry house. - Mod.TG

